ntries remained relatively stable throughout the analyzed period. </p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">In value terms, Mexico ($80M), Brazil ($41M) and Guatemala ($35M) appeared to be the countries with the highest levels of exports in 2017, with a combined 93% share of total exports. </p>\r\n<p><strong>Export Prices by Country</strong></p>\r\n<p>The papaya export price in Latin America and the Caribbean stood at $618 per tonne in 2017, flattening at the previous year. The the papaya export price continues to indicate a relatively flat trend pattern. The growth pace was the most rapid in 2012, an increase of 15% y-o-y. The level of export price peaked at $760 per tonne in 2014; however, from 2015 to 2017, export prices stood at a somewhat lower figure. </p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">There were significant differences in the average export prices amongst the major exporting countries. In 2017, the country with the highest export price was Brazil ($1.1 per kg), while Mexico ($491 per tonne) was amongst the lowest.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">From 2007 to 2017, the most notable rate of growth in terms of export prices was attained by Guatemala (+4.8% per year), while the other leaders experienced a decline in the export price figures.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Papaya Imports</strong><br /><br /><strong>Imports in Latin America and the Caribbean</strong></p>\r\n<p>In 2017, the amount of papayas imported in Latin America and the Caribbean totaled 3.4K tonnes, jumping by 6.6% against the previous year. The total imports indicated a remarkable growth from 2007 to 2017: its volume increased at an average annual rate of +9.2% over the last decade. The trend pattern, however, indicated some noticeable fluctuations being recorded throughout the analyzed period. Based on 2017 figures, the papaya imports increased by +18.2% against 2015 indices. </p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">In value terms, papaya imports totaled $4.9M (<a href=\"https://app.indexbox.io/report?product=080720&amp;region=005\" target=\"_blank\">IndexBox estimates</a>) in 2017. The total imports indicated a strong expansion from 2007 to 2017: its value increased at an average annual rate of +9.2% over the last decade. The trend pattern, however, indicated some noticeable fluctuations being recorded throughout the analyzed period. Based on 2017 figures, the papaya imports increased by +12.2% against 2014 indices. The level of imports peaked in 2017, and are likely to continue its growth in the near future. </p>\r\n<p><strong>Imports by Country</strong></p>\r\n<p>El Salvador was the key importer of papayas in Latin America and the Caribbean, with the volume of imports amounting to 1.7K tonnes, which was near 50% of total imports in 2017. Aruba (416 tonnes) ranks second in terms of the global imports with a 12% share, followed by Argentina (8.2%) and Uruguay (6.8%). The following importers - Honduras (152 tonnes), Paraguay (118 tonnes), Nicaragua (106 tonnes), Barbados (69 tonnes) and Haiti (64 tonnes) together made up 15% of total imports. </p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">From 2007 to 2017, average annual rates of growth with regard to papaya imports into El Salvador stood at +20.6%. At the same time, Aruba (+29.1%), Honduras (+28.3%), Nicaragua (+15.8%), Paraguay (+13.7%), Uruguay (+9.0%), Argentina (+8.1%) and Haiti (+2.9%) displayed positive paces of growth. Moreover, Aruba emerged as the fastest growing importer in Latin America and the Caribbean, with a CAGR of +29.1% from 2007-2017. Barbados experienced a relatively flat trend pattern. From 2007 to 2017, the share of Nicaragua, Paraguay, Uruguay, Honduras, Argentina, Aruba and El Salvador decreased by -2.4%, -2.5%, -3.9%, -4.1%, -4.5%, -11.2% and -42.7% percentage points, while the shares of the other countries remained relatively stable throughout the analyzed period. </p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">In value terms, El Salvador ($2.8M) constitutes the largest market for imported papayas in Latin America and the Caribbean, comprising 57% of global imports. The second position in the ranking was occupied by Argentina ($352K), with a 7.1% share of global imports. It was followed by Aruba, with a 6% share.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Import Prices by Country</strong></p>\r\n<p>The papaya import price in Latin America and the Caribbean stood at $1.4 per kg in 2017, growing by 5.9% against the previous year. The the papaya import price continues to indicate a mild deduction. </p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">There were significant differences in the average import prices amongst the major importing countries. In 2017, the country with the highest import price was Barbados ($1.9 per kg), while Aruba ($714 per tonne) was amongst the lowest.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">From 2007 to 2017, the most notable rate of growth in terms of import prices was attained by Barbados (+6.2% per year), while the other leaders experienced more modest paces of growth.</p>\r\n<p>Source:</p>\r\n<p><a href=\"https://www.indexbox.io/store/latin-america-and-the-caribbean-papayas-market-analysis-forecast-size-trends-and-insights/\" target=\"_blank\"></a></p>', 9, '2019-07-18 22:44:15', 0),
