th Korea (+1.4%) displayed positive paces of growth. Singapore experienced a relatively flat trend pattern. By contrast, Japan (-1.5%) illustrated a downward trend over the same period. From 2007 to 2017, the share of Japan increased by 1.7% percentage points, while Turkey (-1.6%), Taiwan, Chinese (-1.6%), India (-5.5%) and China (-40.1%) saw their share reduced. The shares of the other countries remained relatively stable throughout the analyzed period. </p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\">In value terms, China ($2.6B) constitutes the largest market for imported methanol (methyl alcohol) in Asia, comprising 45% of global imports. The second position in the ranking was occupied by Japan ($596M), with a 10% share of global imports. It was followed by India, with a 9.7% share.</p><b>Import Prices by Country</b><br /><br /><p>In 2017, the methanol import price in Asia amounted to $344 per tonne, going up by 44% against the previous year. The the methanol import price continues to indicate a slight shrinkage. </p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Average import prices varied noticeably amongst the major importing countries. In 2017, major importing countries recorded the following import prices: in China ($344 per tonne) and Singapore ($340 per tonne), while Taiwan, Chinese ($328 per tonne) and South Korea ($331 per tonne) were amongst the lowest.</p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\">From 2007 to 2017, the most notable rate of growth in terms of import prices was attained by China (+1.1% per year), while the other leaders experienced a decline in the import price figures.</p></p><p>Source: <a href=\"https://www.indexbox.io/store/asia-methanol-methyl-alcohol-market-analysis-forecast-size-trends-and-insights/\" target=\"_blank\"></a></p>', 101, '2019-07-18 22:44:15', 3),
