d period. </p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\">In value terms, China ($1.4B), the U.S. ($1.3B) and Mexico ($647M) were the countries with the highest levels of exports in 2017, with a combined 50% share of global exports. These countries were followed by France, Germany, Japan, Norway, the Netherlands, Poland, South Korea and Spain, which together accounted for a further 27%.</p><b>Export Prices by Country</b><br /><br /><p>In 2017, the average optical fiber cables export price amounted to $13 per kg, dropping by -2.6% against the previous year. Over the period from 2007 to 2017, it increased at an average annual rate of +1.0%. </p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\">There were significant differences in the average export prices amongst the major exporting countries. In 2017, the country with the highest export price was the Netherlands ($26 per kg), while China ($7.8 per kg) was amongst the lowest.</p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\">From 2007 to 2017, the most notable rate of growth in terms of export prices was attained by the U.S. (+5.6% per year), while the other global leaders experienced more modest paces of growth.</p><b style=\"font-size: 18px;\">Optical Fiber Cables Imports</b><br /><br /><b>Imports 2007-2017</b><br /><br /><p>In 2017, the amount of optical fiber cables imported worldwide totaled 583K tonnes, growing by 24% against the previous year.</p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\">In value terms, optical fiber cables imports totaled $6.5B (<a href=\"https://app.indexbox.io/report?product=854470&region=0\" target=\"_blank\">IndexBox estimates</a>) in 2017.</p><b>Imports by Country</b><br /><br /><p>The imports of the four major importers of optical fiber cables, namely Mexico, the U.S., Indonesia and Thailand, represented more than third of total import. Canada (24K tonnes), Malaysia (19K tonnes), Singapore (16K tonnes), the Philippines (15K tonnes), Germany (13K tonnes), Egypt (13K tonnes), Russia (12K tonnes) and France (12K tonnes) followed a long way behind the leaders. </p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\">From 2007 to 2017, the most notable rate of growth in terms of imports, amongst the main importing countries, was attained by Indonesia (+41.2% per year), while the other global leaders experienced more modest paces of growth.</p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\">In value terms, the U.S. ($1.2B) constitutes the largest market for imported optical fiber cables worldwide, comprising 18% of global imports. The second position in the ranking was occupied by Mexico ($399M), with a 6.1% share of global imports. It was followed by Canada, with a 5.4% share.</p><b>Import Prices by Country</b><br /><br /><p>The average optical fiber cables import price stood at $11 per kg in 2017, waning by -7.6% against the previous year. In general, the optical fiber cables import price continues to indicate a mild contraction. </p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\">There were significant differences in the average import prices amongst the major importing countries. In 2017, the country with the highest import price was the U.S. ($23 per kg), while Egypt ($1.8 per kg) was amongst the lowest.</p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\">From 2007 to 2017, the most notable rate of growth in terms of import prices was attained by the U.S. (+3.5% per year), while the other global leaders experienced more modest paces of growth.</p></p><p>Source: <a href=\"https://www.indexbox.io/store/world-optical-fiber-cables-market-report-analysis-and-forecast-to-2020/\" target=\"_blank\"></a></p>', 149, '2019-07-18 22:44:15', 0),
