e to indicate a relatively flat trend pattern. In that year, argon exports reached their peak  of $147M. From 2009 to 2017, the growth of argon exports remained at a somewhat lower figure. </p><b>Exports by Country</b><br /><br /><p>In 2017, Germany (65M cubic meters), distantly followed by the Netherlands (38M cubic meters), Belgium (23M cubic meters), the Czech Republic (13M cubic meters) and Austria (9M cubic meters) represented the largest exporters of argon, together mixed up 75% of total exports. The UK (8.4M cubic meters), Poland (6M cubic meters), Finland (4.7M cubic meters), Spain (4.3M cubic meters), Romania (3.8M cubic meters), Sweden (3.6M cubic meters) and France (3.4M cubic meters) occupied the slight share of total exports. </p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\">From 2007 to 2017, the most notable rate of growth in terms of exports, amongst the main exporting countries, was attained by Romania (+42.4% per year), while the other leaders experienced more modest paces of growth.</p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\">In value terms, Germany ($29M), Belgium ($24M) and the Netherlands ($17M) appeared to be the countries with the highest levels of exports in 2017, together comprising 59% of total exports. Austria, the Czech Republic, France, Spain, the UK, Poland, Finland, Romania and Sweden lagged somewhat behind, together comprising a further 26%.</p><b>Export Prices by Country</b><br /><br /><p>The argon export price in the European Union stood at $606 per thousand cubic meters in 2017, surging by 32% against the previous year. The  export price indicated a temperate expansion from 2007 to 2017: its price increased at an average annual rate of +2.6% over the last decade. The trend pattern, however, indicated some noticeable fluctuations being recorded throughout the analyzed period. </p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Export prices varied noticeably by the country of destination; the country with the highest export price was France ($1.4 per cubic meter),