(110, 'Oxygen Market in the EU - Key Insights', '<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><p>IndexBox has just published a new report, <a href=\"https://www.indexbox.io/store/eu-oxygen-market-analysis-forecast-size-trends-and-insights/\">the EU - Oxygen - Market Analysis, Forecast, Size, Trends And Insights</a>. Here is a summary of the report\'s key findings.</p><p></p><p>The revenue of the oxygen market in the European Union amounted to $1.8B in 2017, growing by 9.6% against the previous year. This figure reflects the total revenues of producers and importers (excluding logistics costs, retail marketing costs, and retailers\' margins, which will be included in the final consumer price). Over the period under review, oxygen consumption continues to indicate a noticeable setback. The growth pace was the most rapid in 2008, when the market value increased by 12% against the previous year. In that year, the oxygen market attained its peak level of $2.8B. From 2009 to 2017, the growth of the oxygen market remained at a somewhat lower figure. </p><b>Production in the EU</b><br /><br /><p>In 2017, approx. 12B cubic meters of oxygen were produced in the European Union; going down by -4.7% against the previous year. Over the period under review, oxygen production continues to indicate a measured slump. </p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\"></p></p><b>Exports in the EU</b><br /><br /><p>The exports stood at 832M cubic meters in 2017, declining by -6% against the previous year. In general, oxygen exports, however, continue to indicate a relatively flat trend pattern. </p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\">In value terms, oxygen exports totaled $131M (<a href=\"https://app.indexbox.io/report?product=280440&region=155\" target=\"_blank\">IndexBox estimates</a>) in 2017. Over the period under review, oxygen exports, however, continue to indicate a relatively flat trend pattern. In that year, oxygen exports attained their peak  of $159M. From 2009 to 2017, the growth of oxygen exports remained at a somewhat lower figure. </p><b>Exports by Country</b><br /><br /><p>Belgium (230M cubic meters) and France (175M cubic meters) represented roughly 49% of total exports of oxygen in 2017. Germany (48M cubic meters) ranks next in terms of the total exports with a 5.8% share, followed by Croatia (5.7%), the Czech Republic (5.7%), Poland (5%), the Netherlands (5%) and Austria (4.8%). Portugal (30M cubic meters) occupied a minor share of total exports. </p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\">From 2007 to 2017, the most notable rate of growth in terms of exports, amongst the main exporting countries, was attained by Poland, while the other leaders experienced more modest paces of growth.</p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\">In value terms, Belgium ($34M), France ($26M) and the Netherlands ($10M) constituted the countries with the highest levels of exports in 2017, together accounting for 54% of total exports. Germany, Portugal, the Czech Republic, Austria, Poland and Croatia lagged somewhat behind, together accounting for a further 27%.</p><b>Export Prices by Country</b><br /><br /><p>In 2017, the oxygen export price in the European Union amounted to $157 per thousand cubic meters, increasing by 14% against the previous year. Over the last decade, the oxygen export price, however, continues to indicate a mild decline. </p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Export prices varied noticeably by the country of origin; the country with the highest export price was Portugal ($254 per thousand cubic meters), while Croatia ($64 per thousand cubic meters) was amongst the lowest.</p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\">From 2007 to 2017, the most notable rate of growth in terms of export prices was attained by the Netherlands, while the other leaders experienced more modest paces of growth.</p><b>Imports in the EU</b><br /><br /><p>In 2017, approx. 723M cubic meters of oxygen were imported in the European Union; increasing by 22% against the previous year. Over the last decade, oxygen imports continue to indicate a relatively flat trend pattern. </p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\">In value terms, oxygen imports amounted to $122M (<a href=\"https://app.indexbox.io/report?product=280440&region=155\" target=\"_blank\">IndexBox estimates</a>) in 2017.</p><b>Imports by Country</b><br /><br /><p>In 2017, Germany (188M cubic meters), distantly followed by France (114M cubic meters), Luxembourg (85M cubic meters), Slovenia (61M cubic meters), Belgium (55M cubic meters), the Czech Republic (44M cubic meters) and Slovakia (42M cubic meters) were the main importers of oxygen, together creating 81% of total imports. </p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\">From 2007 to 2017, the most notable rate of growth in terms of imports, amongst the main importing countries, was attained by the Czech Republic, while the other leaders experienced more modest paces of growth.</p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\">In value terms, Germany ($24M), France ($17M) and Luxembourg ($9.6M) constituted the countries with the highest levels of imports in 2017, together accounting for 42% of total imports. These countries were followed by Belgium, Slovenia, the Czech Republic and Slovakia, which together accounted for a further 20%.</p><b>Import Prices by Country</b><br /><br /><p>In 2017, the oxygen import price in the European Union amounted to $169 per thousand cubic meters, going down by -10.1% against the previous year. In general, the oxygen import price, however, continues to indicate a relatively flat trend pattern. </p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Average import prices varied somewhat amongst the major importing countries. In 2017, major importing countries recorded the following import prices: in Belgium ($147 per thousand cubic meters) and France ($147 per thousand cubic meters), while Slovenia ($103 per thousand cubic meters) and Slovakia ($111 per thousand cubic meters) were amongst the lowest.</p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\">From 2007 to 2017, the most notable rate of growth in terms of import prices was attained by Slovenia, while the other leaders experienced a decline in the import price figures.</p></p><p>Source: <a href=\"https://www.indexbox.io/store/eu-oxygen-market-analysis-forecast-size-trends-and-insights/\" target=\"_blank\"></a></p>', 101, '2019-07-18 22:44:15', 0),
(111, 'EU Shampoo Market | France And Germany Remain The Largest Consuming Markets', '<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><p>IndexBox has just published a new report, <a href=\"https://www.indexbox.io/store/eu-shampoos-market-report-analysis-and-forecast-to-2020/\">the EU - Shampoos - Market Analysis, Forecast, Size, Trends and Insights</a>. Here is a summary of the report\'s key findings.</p><p></p><p>The revenue of the shampoo market in the European Union amounted to $1.8B in 2017, going up by 4.6% against the previous year. This figure reflects the total revenues of producers and importers (excluding logistics costs, retail marketing costs, and retailers\' margins, which will be included in the final consumer price). Overall, shampoo consumption continues to indicate a slight deduction. The most prominent rate of growth was recorded in 2008, with an increase of 11% against the previous year. In that year, the shampoo market attained its peak level of $2.4B. From 2009 to 2017, the growth of the shampoo market failed to regain its momentum. </p><b>Production in the EU</b><br /><br /><p>In 2017, the amount of shampoos produced in the European Union stood at 827K tonnes, waning by -4.6% against the previous year. Over the last decade, shampoo production continues to indicate a mild setback. </p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\"></p></p><b>Exports in the EU</b><br /><br /><p>The exports stood at 817K tonnes in 2017, remaining relatively unchanged against the previous year. The total export volume increased at an average annual rate of +1.2% from 2007 to 2017; the trend pattern remained relatively stable, with only minor fluctuations over the period under review. The growth pace was the most rapid in 2010, when the exports increased by 12% year-to-year. Over the period under review, shampoo exports attained their maximum in 2017, and are expected to retain its growth in the immediate term. </p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\">In value terms, shampoo exports stood at $2.5B (<a href=\"https://app.indexbox.io/report?product=330510&region=155\" target=\"_blank\">IndexBox estimates</a>) in 2017. The total export value increased at an average annual rate of +2.3% from 2007 to 2017; the trend pattern remained relatively stable, with only minor fluctuations over the period under review. The level of exports peaked in 2017, and are likely to continue its growth in the near future. </p><b>Exports by Country</b><br /><br /><p>In 2017, France (150K tonnes), Germany (131K tonnes), Italy (107K tonnes), Poland (105K tonnes), Romania (77K tonnes), the UK (56K tonnes), Spain (47K tonnes), Belgium (40K tonnes) and the Netherlands (29K tonnes) were the largest exporters of shampoos in the European Union, achieving 91% of total export. </p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\">From 2007 to 2017, the most notable rate of growth in terms of exports, amongst the main exporting countries, was attained by Romania, while the other leaders experienced more modest paces of growth.</p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\">In value terms, Germany ($404M), France ($368M) and Italy ($265M) appeared to be the countries with the highest levels of exports in 2017, together accounting for 42% of total exports. The UK, Poland, Romania, Belgium, Spain and the Netherlands lagged somewhat behind, together accounting for a further 47%.</p><b>Export Prices by Country</b><br /><br /><p>The shampoo export price in the European Union stood at $3 per kg in 2017, increasing by 7.5% against the previous year. Over the last decade, it increased at an average annual rate of +1.1%. </p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\">There were significant differences in the average export prices amongst the major exporting countries. In 2017, the country with the highest export price was the Netherlands ($4,835 per tonne), while Poland ($2,208 per tonne) was amongst the lowest.</p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\">From 2007 to 2017, the most notable rate of growth in terms of export prices was attained by the UK, while the other leaders experienced more modest paces of growth.</p><b>Imports in the EU</b><br /><br /><p>In 2017, shampoo imports in the European Union totaled 628K tonnes, going up by 1.6% against the previous year. The total import volume increased at an average annual rate of +3.0% from 2007 to 2017; however, the trend pattern indicated some noticeable fluctuations being recorded in certain years. </p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\">In value terms, shampoo imports amounted to $1.8B (<a href=\"https://app.indexbox.io/report?product=330510&region=155\" target=\"_blank\">IndexBox estimates</a>) in 2017.</p><b>Imports by Country</b><br /><br /><p>The UK (83K tonnes), Germany (68K tonnes), Poland (55K tonnes), France (53K tonnes), Spain (51K tonnes), Belgium (51K tonnes), Italy (47K tonnes) and the Netherlands (45K tonnes) represented roughly 72% of total imports of shampoos in 2017. The Czech Republic (21K tonnes), Portugal (20K tonnes), Ireland (17K tonnes) and Sweden (15K tonnes) held a relatively small share of total imports. </p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\">From 2007 to 2017, the most notable rate of growth in terms of imports, amongst the main importing countries, was attained by France, while the other leaders experienced more modest paces of growth.</p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\">In value terms, the largest shampoo importing markets worldwide were the UK ($231M), Germany ($227M) and the Netherlands ($147M), together comprising 34% of total imports. France, Poland, Spain, Belgium, Italy, Sweden, Ireland, the Czech Republic and Portugal lagged somewhat behind, together comprising a further 46%.</p><b>Import Prices by Country</b><br /><br /><p>The shampoo import price in the European Union stood at $2.8 per kg in 2017, jumping by 8.1% against the previous year. Overall, the shampoo import price, however, continues to indicate a relatively flat trend pattern. </p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\">There were significant differences in the average import prices amongst the major importing countries. In 2017, the country with the highest import price was Sweden ($3,973 per tonne), while Poland ($2,245 per tonne) was amongst the lowest.</p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\">From 2007 to 2017, the most notable rate of growth in terms of import prices was attained by the Netherlands, while the other leaders experienced more modest paces of growth.</p></p><p>Source: <a href=\"https://www.indexbox.io/store/eu-shampoos-market-report-analysis-and-forecast-to-2020/\" target=\"_blank\"></a></p>', 106, '2019-07-18 22:44:15', 0),
(112, 'MDF Market in China - Key Insights', '<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><p>IndexBox has just published a new report, <a href=\"https://www.indexbox.io/store/china-mdf-market-report-analysis-and-forecast-to-2020-/\">the China - MDF - Market Analysis, Forecast, Size, Trends and Insights</a>. Here is a summary of the report\'s key findings.</p><p></p><p>The revenue of the mdf market in China amounted to $19B in 2017, coming down by -8.8% against the previous year. This figure reflects the total revenues of producers and importers (excluding logistics costs, retail marketing costs, and retailers\' margins, which will be included in the final consumer price). Overall, mdf consumption continues to indicate a remarkable increase. The growth pace was the most rapid in 2008, with an increase of 28% year-to-year. The mdf consumption peaked of $23B in 2014; however, from 2015 to 2017, it failed to regain its momentum. </p></p><b>Exports from China</b><br /><br /><p>In 2017, approx. 2.4M cubic meters of mdf were exported from China; approximately mirroring the previous year. In general, mdf exports continue to indicate a relatively flat trend pattern. The growth pace was the most rapid in 2011, when exports increased by 33% against the previous year. The exports peaked of 3.2M cubic meters in 2012; however, from 2013 to 2017, it failed to regain its momentum. </p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\">In value terms, mdf exports totaled $1B (<a href=\"https://app.indexbox.io/report?product=441112h441114&region=156\" target=\"_blank\">IndexBox estimates</a>) in 2017. Overall, the total exports indicated a temperate increase from 2007 to 2017: its value increased at an average annual rate of +0.2% over the last decade. The trend pattern, however, indicated some noticeable fluctuations throughout the analyzed period. Based on 2017 figures, the mdf exports decreased by -30.0% against 2014 indices. Over the period under review, the mdf exports attained its peak figure level of $1.